description.text:
A "better" receiver-antenna-tube-mount for the Armattan Chameleon frame. Designed to be placed underneath the rear aluminum VTX antenna mount.

Designed to be used with the FrSky XSR Receiver. It should work with the X4R-SB but I have not personally tested it.

*The new R-XSR antennas are closer together: This mount will still work with the R-XSR although it was not designed with it in mind.

This version has longer antenna tube guides with a ridge on the end of the guide, allowing you to use heat-shrink to hold the antenna tube in place. The ridge on the end gives the heat-shrink something to grip and allows you to use a zip-tie to really secure the heat-shrink even further.

For best results: Print in the same orientation as it will go into the frame, with supports to help hold up the tube guides.

title: Tronxy X3 or X3A Bed Upgrade Remix

description.text:
So this is my Bed Remix, I used parts from Kencam and Kryptonit3. Kencam's Bed_Support was slightly modified to fit the acrylic bed with writing on it "X3" and to use screws and nuts to fasten the bearings. I made Rod_Holders that are nice and small but keeps the rod height the same as Kencams Rod Holders. I made an original Endstop that makes it so you won't have to make changes in firmware!

Things needed are:

  • 400X8mm Linear Rods X2
  • Nema 17 Stepper Motor Steel Bracket
  • Original M2 Machine Screws and Nuts from Endstop
  • M3 25mm Machine Screws X4
  • M3 Nuts X4
  • M4 28mm Machine Screw + Original Nut, Washers and Bearing for Belt.
  • M4 8mm Machine Screws X2
  • M4 16mm Machine Screws X4
  • M5 10mm Machine Screws X2
  • M6 18mm Machine Screws X4
  • M6 Nuts X4
  • M4 T-Nuts X11
  • M5 T-Nuts X2
  • GT2 Belt (6mm)
    All parts where printed at 100% Infill accept the Bed_Support which was printed with 25% Infill.

Thanks goes out to the original designers!! :)

description.text:
This is the ring to install a 4.35mm 'gopro' style lens to the Hubsan H109s Camera. Lens are available in sites like aliexpress or ebay for a few euros.
These lens effectively reduce camera's field of view, thus reducing the barrel effect (a bit too pronounced in the stock lenses). The video quality will be also improved due to the improved quality lenses (stock camera uses cheap glass).

Standard GoPro lenses are 14mm in diameter, smaller than the diameter of the stock camera. When such lenses are used in the hubsan camera, the space between the lens and the camera body leaves a gap from which excessive dust and moisture may enter the camera itself.

The adaptor proposed here fits perfectly and fills such gap, preventing dust entering the camera and protecting the component inside.

Designed in Freecad, FCStd file is included in this page. Please feel free to modify the project as you like.

description.text:
This pineapple may be used to demonstrate natural spiral patterns, and has ten spirals in each direction. It is made from two shapes: a truncated pentagonal pyramid and an elliptic cone.

by H. Chutter, 12/14/17

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

Rostock MAX v3

I started with by tiling an array of truncated pentagonal pyramids around an ellipsoid. Then I twisted the entire object 137.5 degrees. The leaves were similarly created with an array of flattened cones rotated around a cylinder.

One of the most challenging parts of creating this was finding the best angle at which to twist the ellipsoid in order to create the most accurate pineapple appearance. The original plan was to be a correct representation of the way the Fibonacci sequence appears in a pineapple, but there were not enough spirals to make it correct. It also took some time to find a good distance to set the pentagons and cones apart when making the arrays.

description.text:
--- Description ---
This a weighted poker card capper. It is placed on your hole cards during a hand to make sure they are not accidentally folded. The base is designed with the same diameter (39mm) as a standard size poker chip so this will stack perfectly on your chips when not in use.

This design is a great white shark leaping to attack a dollar symbol.
If you like this you may want to checkout my collection of card cappers

--- Printing ---
1) Print one of each part.
2) The dollar sign does not need supports.
3) I printed the holder (upside down) and base with line support material spaced at 4.5mm.

--- Assembly ---
1) The holder is designed to have 4 nickels placed inside of it as ballast prior to it being snapped into the base.
2) With the nickels inside the holder snap the base over the top of it.
3) Put glue on the bottom of the shark and push it onto the tab in the middle of the water. The fins on the shark should slid into the slots in the water (the shark has to face the correct direction; it can't be rotated 180°).
4) Put glue on the cylinder that sticks up from the dollar sign and also underneath/behind the sharks upper teeth. Slide the dollar sign cylinder into the throat of the shark and use slight pressure to push the dollar sign under the shark's upper teeth.

Enjoy and if you print one please post a picture!

This model demonstrates how adding different fractions adds up to 1 even though they have different denominators. The model was designed as a manipulative to be used in a middle school or high school math classroom to help students understand fractions.

I designed this model by coming up with an inner radius for my base. I then used an equation to determine what radius my fraction pieces should have in order to fit in the base. For the prototype, the base had a radius of 20 and the fraction pieces should have a radius of 19.3. The final version has a base with a radius of 40 and the fraction pieces should have a radius of 39.3.

*not all of the pieces were designed with this radius due to challenges. and not all the pieces have the radius that was input into Rhino

As the fraction pieces got smaller, I started having a problem with them all fitting into the base. I believe this may be due to the turns that the printer has to make in order to print the pieces. I had to use a smaller radius for some of the smaller pieces on both the prototype and the final.

This is the second iteration of my E3D extruder for the Solidoodle. It incorporates a more streamlined design by integrating the 30mm heatsink fan into the front of the assembly, allowing for easy wire management. Future changes could include: Better wire management
Better fan duct placement
Any other suggestions

Due to the offset needed by the large size of the E3D heatsink fins, you will need to move your extruder stepper motor forward by around 4mm. This means that you will also have to unscrew the setscrew in the filament drive gear to move it further down the stepper motor shaft so that it aligns with the new offset hole. This may make the entire extruder assembly "front heavy", but it seems that it is working fine so far.  
I'm hoping to eventually redesign it from scratch to eliminate some workarounds that had to be done to get the mashup to work correctly. Please feel free to comment on any ideas you might have on improving this.

Here is a cover for the Ender 2 Power Supply.

be careful, work with power off. insulate connections. If you are working with AC line voltage, it can kill you, so either know what you are doing or seek help!

The idea of this project is to create a wearable, water resistant, animated rainbow light strip to be shamelessly be exploited for money during pride festivities. Based on an Adafruit Neopixel strip, an Arduino nano and any standard 5v mobile power bank, this silly device can keep the proud individual dancing for hours on end.

The core of this project is the Arduino sketch that creates a rainbow corresponding to the number of LEDs in your WS2011b (or similar) light strip. The main feature is the algorithm that uses trigonometry to create a colour wheel where the circumference is equal to the number of LEDs in the strip. It isn't 100 percent exact, simply because the relationship between PWM level and brightness of an LED is not anywhere near linear. That said, you don't get the smoothest blend between the colours, but the major colours show through clearly. In brief, the formula for creating the colour wheel is essentially:

x = 2 Pi / (LED# +1) (where LED# is address of the current LED in the strip).
Red=cos(x) Maximum_Power_Level
Green=cos(x + 2Pi/3) Maximum_Power_Level
Blue=cos(x + 4Pi/3) Maximum_Power_Level.

In other words, the Red, Green and Blue values are offset from each other by 120 degrees.

The other second algorithm in the sketch simply shifts whatever is on the strip to the next pixel.

This sketch relies on the NeoPixel library. Kudos to Adafruit for the amazing hardware, libraries and community support.

For what its worth, I used Microsoft 3D paint to create a hollow cylinder to contain the Arduino nano and the wires and capacitor. It isn't the most ergonomic model and the holes could be a little bit larger to fit all the wires. I'm more than happy to hear recommendations for a more suitable enclosure.

Finally, the wiring diagram is exactly the same as what Adafruit recommends for connection of its NeoPixel strip. i.e. 100uF capacitor and a 230 Ohm resistor.

title: Ender 4 Extrudermotor Halterung mit Silentblock - Mounting plate extension for the extruder motor

description.text:
English description below...

DEUTSCH:

Erhöhung der originalen Montageplatte vom Extrudermotor.
Zusätzlich wurden noch zwei Silentblöcke montiert. Die Motorgeräusche vom Extruder werden somit nicht mehr auf den Rahmen übertragen.
In den Dateien ist auch eine höhere Variante ohne Silentblöcke vorhanden, oder wenn man noch weiter heraus möchte.

  • Das Filament läuft jetzt mittig in den Extrudermotor.
  • Der Motor sitzt nicht mehr "im" Rahmen, somit kann man diesen leichter mit einer Platte schließen.
  • Leiserer Betrieb!

Silentblöcke gibt es bei eBay oder dem örtlichen Eisenwarenhändler.
Ich habe die Variante mit beidseitig Außengewinde M5 und den Abmessungen 15x15mm gewählt. Nicht länger nehmen, denn Silentblöcke sind relativ weich und somit eigentlich nicht für horizontale Befestigung gedacht! Der Motor könnte dann herunter hängen.

Die Bohrungen zum Befestigen am Rahmen sind für M5 Schrauben konzipiert.
Die Sacklöcher für die Silentblöcke sind 4,7mm und somit können diese direkt mit ein wenig Kraft eingedreht werden (kein Gewindeschneiden notwendig).
Passende Hammermuttern M5 - Nut 6 gibt es auch bei eBay.

ENGLISH:

In addition, two vibration isolators were added to the mount. The vibration (noise) from the extruder motor is no longer transmitted to the frame.

The files also include a longer version for either use without the vibration isolators, or if you want to mount the extruder motor even further out.

  • The filament now runs centrally into the extruder motor. (better aligned with the spool)
  • The extruder motor is no longer "in" the frame, so it is easier to close up the frame with insulation.
  • Quieter operation!

Vibration isolators are available from eBay or a local hardware retailer.
I have selected the type that have male M5 threads on both sides and measure 15x15mm. Do not get one any longer than that, because vibration isolators are relatively flexible, so they are not intended for horizontal mounting! The extruder motor would bend downward.

The mounting holes on the frame are designed for M5 screws.
The blind holes for the vibration isolators are 4.7mm and so they can be screwed in directly with a little force (no threading necessary).
Matching hammer nuts M5 - Nut 6 are also available on eBay.

title: CreaLight - LED light for any CR-10 frame

description.text:
The CreaLight is meant to be used with (USB) LED strips. The light bar can be turned to change the angle at what needs to be lid.

Cheap LED strips usually don't stick well which is why I added friction fit "clipper" clips to keep the strips inside the light bar. The "corner" pieces aren't strictly necessary but will add friction to keep the lighting angle in the chosen position. Be sure to watch out for the cable slot when installing the light and please use 10mm velcro strips for cable management.

The camera mount should work for most action cameras but had been modelled with the Quelima SQ11 in mind: SQ11mount. Use M5-25 hex head screws and M5 hex nuts to populate "screw" and "nut" of the camera mount.

The CreaLight will probably also work with many other printers based on open-frame v-slot extruded aluminum bars. I modelled a version of this arm for the Prusa i3 printers: PruLight. Recently I added a slightly different version for the Creality Ender 2: EnLight

I might add shorter and longer light bars in the future.

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Notes:

Actually I printed the light bars on a Prusa i3 MK2s but should print without issues on the Creality CR-10 as these printers are very similar in design. The arms in the photos as well as the action camera mount system were printed on the Creality CR-10.

To end up with the very same look you will have to slice the arms with 10% to 20% honeycomb infill (for example in Slic3r) using 3 or more perimeters and no top or bottom layers. Be sure to have retraction around 20mm/s for 6mm length to prevent nasty stringing.

The light bar as well as all the other parts work well with default settings for 0.1mm layer height but can tend to get a bit tight at 0.2mm height or more.

As easy as 1, 2, 3 ...

Just put a USB LED strip with the USB cable oriented towards the cable slot into the light bar and carefully cut it to lengths. Then remove the protection and glue it to the light bar. Add the corner pieces to the corners and two clippers about equally spaced apart from each other to keep the LED strip in place. Be sure to not cover LEDs or electric components but just the strip/tape instead.

In case your LED strip is not flat but a few mm heigh be sure to clip the clippers to length.

Use 10mm velcro for cable management.
